listing.description:
Bring perspective to due dates with the Calendar Power-Up for Trello. Whether you are planning a conference, managing an editorial calendar, or organizing a family vacation, the Calendar Power-Up letâ€™s you display cards with due dates in a weekly or monthly calendar view. Easily prioritize cards by dragging and dropping them on the calendar to automatically update their due dates, and export your Trello calendar to third party apps with an iCalendar link.

- Display and filter cards with due dates in a weekly or monthly calendar view.

- Manage due dates by dragging and dropping cards on the calendar.

- Easily see completed tasks by marking due dates complete.

- Export a boardâ€™s calendar to third party calendars with each boardâ€™s unique iCalendar link.

- The Calendar Power-Up is supported on the web and iOS and Android mobile devices.

listing.name: Planyway: Calendar, Timeline, Time Tracking
listing.description:
Looking for a tool for managing your teams and projects? Planyway is exactly what you need! From coordinating multiple boards and managing workload to building a roadmap and tracking time efforts - you found the only power-up you need to do it all in Trello.

## Timeline

Get better visibility across Trello boards to manage your teams and projects at different angles. Simply drag your Trello tasks to our powerful timeline and orchestrate work much faster, easier, and with less effort.

[![Timeline features](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-timeline-drag-and-drop.gif)](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-timeline-drag-and-drop.gif)

[![Timeline](https://bit.ly/3f6Zg7c)](https://bit.ly/3f6Zg7c)

## Calendar

Schedule deadlines on a single team calendar to make sure that all tasks will get done on time. Connect other calendars like Google, Outlook, etc. to see your full availability on one plate and never miss a thing.

[![Calendar week](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-calendar-card-create.gif)](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-calendar-card-create.gif)

[![Calendar features](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-calendar-features.png)](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-calendar-features.png)

## Board swimlanes

Personalize boards with swimlanes to get better clarity into your workflow. Group cards by member or label and structure work the way you need.

[![Board swimlanes](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-swimlanes-labels-drag-card.gif)](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-swimlanes-labels-drag-card.gif)

## Time Tracking

Get everything you need to gain more insights into how much time your team really spends on tasks. Make use of this data to charge clients and control team productivity to achieve better results. 

[![Time tracking list](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-time-track.gif)](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-time-track.gif)

[![Time tracking features](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-time-tracking-features.png)](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-time-tracking-features.png)

[![Open trello card](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-trello-card-timer.gif)](https://files.planyway.com/common/powerup-store-trello-card-timer.gif)

## Sample Use Cases

The beauty of Planyway is its flexibility. No matter what your industry is, you can manage any workflow with ease. Any doubts? Check out some of our use cases below or visit our website for more!

listing.name: BigPicture
listing.description:
> Please be informed that all our development work related to BigPicture Trello platform has been temporarily withheld till the end of 2021. It does not mean that we gave up on the development of our Power-Up! We are intensively working on tasks that will enable us to enrich BigPicture with additional functionalities. [Click here to read more](https://wiki.softwareplant.com/doc/all/trello-bigpicture-power-up/bigpicture-trello-product-roadmap).


**BigPicture** empowers you to dynamically manage project **Work Breakdown Structure**, **filter and display** the selected data the way you want it; **Milestones,  markers, critical path, progress and custom views** let you quickly evaluate your project status.


![Overview](https://s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/softwareplant-cdn/bigpicture/trello/icons/INTROTRELLOFILM-min.gif)
Enhance the project management experience using **BigPicture**, a **PPM Power-Up** tool. The top-selling Jira plugin is now available for Trello. Plan your tasks using marvelous and colorful Gantt charts, automate your work or keep track of all the changes using different modes. Create **dependencies or structure** your tasks using **drag&drop**.


#**With BigPicture you can:**

- Schedule your tasks using **drag&drop**
- **Automate** your work or work in **manual mode**
- Create advanced **Work Breakdown Structure**
- Link your tasks using **dependency links**
- **Customize** the view
- Add more tasks using **Artificial tasks**
- **Sort and group** your cards

![Grouping tasks](https://s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/softwareplant-cdn/bigpicture/trello/icons/GROUPLAND-min.gif)

![Grouping tasks](https://s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/softwareplant-cdn/bigpicture/trello/icons/LINKLAND-min.gif)

#**How does it work?**

**BigPicture** displays **Trello Cards** in a form of Tasks which can be easily allocated on the Gantt chart accompanied by the **WBS (Work Breakdown Structure)** panel. Since Cards are allocated to Boards, we could take an approach in which a Board represents a certain project. This Power-Up is capable of displaying a number of Cards from **multiple Boards** (projects) in form of Tasks on the **Gantt chart**.


![WorkBreakdownStructure](https://s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/softwareplant-cdn/bigpicture/trello/icons/BOARDLAND.gif)


#**Who is this for?**

Boost up your **Teams'** productivity and grow! Wheather your team is small or large take advantage of all Trello's features and combine it with professional tools.

Check BigPicture Power-Up [website](https://softwareplant.com/), [documentation](https://wiki.softwareplant.com/display/DOCUMENTATION/About+BigPicture+Trello), [EULA](https://wiki.softwareplant.com/display/DOCUMENTATION/BigPicture+Trello+EULA) and [Privacy Policy](https://wiki.softwareplant.com/display/DOCUMENTATION/BigPicture+Trello+Privacy+Policy).

listing.name: Agile Tools by Corrello
listing.description:
# Free Agile Points and WIP limits for Trello

Agile Tools by Corrello allows you to add story points and WIP Limits to Trello. It is fully integrated with Corrello [Scrum and Kanban Charts](https://trello.com/power-ups/568c2b6c7d2758a55ac48c98/agile-scrum-kanban-dashboards-charts-corrello) **[burndowns](https://app.getcorrello.com/Burndown?utm_source=trello&utm_medium=directory&utm_campaign=agile_tools_powerup_burndown)**, **[CFDs](https://getcorrello.com/cumulative-flow-diagram?utm_source=trello&utm_medium=directory&utm_campaign=agile_tools_powerup_cfd)**, **burnups**, and **[cycle time](https://app.getcorrello.com/cycle-time?utm_source=trello&utm_medium=directory&utm_campaign=agile_tools_powerup_cycletime)** charts. 

Agile Tools is **completely free** and is the perfect Power-Up for Scrum or Kanban teams using Trello (or even teams blending a mix of Scrum and Kanban :) )

Add the power-up today to take benefit of these great features:

- **Story points on Cards**. Set on the back of cards, shown on the front. Includes the ability to use a colour scale to large vs small Cards are easy to spot.
- **One click migration of story points from Scrum for Trello** or any other tool which stores points in the Card titles.
- **WIP limits** easily set in the power-up settings, or in list titles using numbers in []'s
-  **Count of Cards or Points in each List** useful for quick overview of upcoming work or past velocities.

![Features GIF](https://app.getcorrello.com/manifests/agiletools/images/agiletools.gif)

## Story Points for Trello

Easily set and see story points on all your cards. Points are shown on the front of your cards and can be easily set on the back. By default we will allow people to select any Fibonacci number for their estimates, or enter their own value. You can also set the points available for your team if you don't want to use the typical Fibonacci sequence we default to.

![Story Points on cards and lists](https://app.getcorrello.com/manifests/agiletools/images/list_points.png)

You can also opt to use a colour scale for the points on your cards. This makes it easy to see visually which cards have higher or lower estimates. We can also highlight any unestimated cards in red. This makes it really easy to spot unestimated cards for an estimation session, or to highlight unestimated cards which are being added to a sprint.


## Estimate your Scrum Sprints

Clicking on the Agile Tools button in Trello will show the number of points currently in each list. This makes it super simple to check how many points you have assigned to your current (or future) sprint, and how many are in progress right now. You can also see the number of points completed in previous sprints, we recommend creating a new 'done' list for each sprint if you want to track past velocity easily. 

Also, if you have future planned work estimated in lists on your board you can easily see from the Agile Tools button how many points are in each upcoming list.

## WIP Limits for Trello

If all you want are WIP limits you could also check out our [Kanban WIP](https://trello.com/power-ups/5e621e477907d7774380f551/kanban-wip-by-corrello) Power-Up for Trello.

Setting WIP limits is a very common approach in Kanban to encourage teams to focus on finishing work before starting something new. It can also be useful on Scrum teams for the same reason.

With Agile Tools you can set WIP limits for individual lists in Trello. We will show the number of cards and the WIP limit on the front of each card and highlight when you are at or over the WIP limit for that list

![Set WIP limits for Trello](https://app.getcorrello.com/manifests/agiletools/images/wiplimits.png)

## Integrates with Corrello for Burndowns, CFDs and more...

Agile Tools for Trello is the only power-up which integrates with [Corrello](https://trello.com/power-ups/568c2b6c7d2758a55ac48c98/agile-scrum-kanban-dashboards-charts-corrello) - Dashboards for Agile teams using Trello. Corrello can plot your Story Points on a Burndown, plus send daily emails with your latest Burndown, WIP, Slow Cards etc. Track cycle times, release burnups, your Cumulative Flow Diagram and more with a just few clicks :)

![Agile Metrics for Trello](https://app.getcorrello.com/public/images/powerup/cfd.png)

-----------

**Got questions?** drop us a line agiletoolspowerup@getcorrello.com


## What are people saying about Agile Tools?

*Software development is a messy process, planning is continuous and new Trello cards get added by the team on a daily basis. It is great to be able to **spot all unestimated cards with one click** and keep the scrum board estimated at all times. It is also extremely useful to get an **overview of the amount of points currently allocated in each Trello column**. This feature comes very handy when trying to understand whether we're putting too much work on our shoulders for our next sprint or whether it's possible to increase our scope.*
- Valentino Giudice (PM **Natural Cycles**)

----

## What are Story Points?

Story points are a way of estimating work which breaks the link between hours/days to complete and the number on the estimation. So while you may expect roughly the same number of story points completed per week for a team, you wouldn't talk about estimates in terms of hours or days.

This is important as it makes it easier for the team to discuss the estimate without getting hung up on how long the card will take to complete. Instead they can compare that task with previous completed tasks and decide which previous tasks it is most similar to in terms of the complexity/effort to deliver. Then they assign the same number of story points as those most similar previous tasks to this new task.

If you estimate in terms of hours/days it can be very easy to get drawn into discussions of **how** the work will be done and justifying the time estimate to a very high level of precision. Or to have people feel they will look stupid for thinking something will take longer than another person suggests. By discussing points relative to another completed task it becomes a bit more abstract and easier for people to have open discussions.

## How to estimate Story Points?

There are many ways to generate the estimates. The only hard and fast rule is that the estimate should be created by the team who will complete the work.

Some popular/common ways to estimate story points

### Planning poker

In planning poker each team member has cards for each of the story point options (typically 1,2,3,5,8,13,21). Each task to be estimated is shown to the team, questions are asked and answered until the team is ready to estimate it. Any additional details brought out in the discussion should be added to the task in Trello (ie limits on what is to be done, or clarifications etc.) Each team member then plays one of their cards face down. When everyone is ready you turn over the cards and see the estimates. If everyone is in agreement the estimate is added to the card. If there is disagreement you typically get the people with the highest and lowest estimates to discuss their differences until you can reach some agreement within the group. 

Having a set of reference cards is very useful here, so people can see examples of past cards which were a 1, 2, 5, etc. People can then talk about the size of each card in comparison to the reference examples.

Planning poker is a very thorough way of estimating work for a Scrum team, but can take a long time to get through a lot of cards. However, the discussions which take the time to get through would need to happen eventually. It is better to have them during a planning session than in the middle of a sprint and only then realise a card is a lot more complex than expected!

### Story Point Buckets

This is a lot more interactive and allows for less discussion up front, but can help in getting through a lot of cards in a more efficient way.

Your team will need space in front of a wall to do this and be able to stick and move cards on the wall. Start by creating buckets for each Story point value (1,2,3,5,etc) with one or more reference cards for each. Place these horizontally across the wall. The area below each story point card is it's bucket.

Then place the cards to be estimated where the team can get them and let them start picking up cards and putting them into the bucket they think is correct. Team members can also move cards they think are in the wrong bucket. After some time you should have a bunch of cards on which the team is agreed on an estimate, and some others which different people want to move. You can simply assign the relevant points to the cards which there is agreement on. Then discuss estimates on the more contentious ones.


## Why use fibonacci number for Story Points?

Great question! Fibonacci numbers are used by Scrum teams as they have the property of lower precision as the numbers increase. When comparing a task estimated as a 1 or a 2 it makes sense to worry about that extra point as it doubles the estimate. But for a task estimated as an 8 the difference between 8 and 9 is less significant. Instead we want to ask is this more like an 8, or more like a 13?

## How many story points to a day?

Although you will have a rough average for the number of story points a team can complete in a week, you shouldn't really think of it in terms of points per day or anything like that. And certainly you can't compare points from one team to another team, since the way they estimate them could lead to large differences (one teams 5 point card could be a 13 for another, even if they would complete it in the same time).

----

## Our other Power-Ups for Trello

**Corrello [Scrum and Kanban charts](https://trello.com/power-ups/568c2b6c7d2758a55ac48c98/agile-scrum-kanban-dashboards-charts-corrello)**. Burndowns, CFDs, Cycle Time, Release Forecasts and more.

**[Kanban WIP](https://trello.com/power-ups/5e621e477907d7774380f551/kanban-wip-by-corrello)**. Allows you to set up WIP limits which will apply across multiple lists.

**[Burndown Charts for Trello](https://trello.com/power-ups/5eda444d3be9d07a01eb82a4/burndowns-by-corrello)**. The best Burndown Charts for Trello, with daily Slack and Email updates.

**Blue Cat [Trello Reporting](https://trello.com/power-ups/5d9c90aa18965066fcd44730/reports-by-blue-cat)**. Our general purpose Reporting solution for Trello. Build the charts you want, drag and drop to create the dashboard how your team needs it.

**[Time in List](https://trello.com/power-ups/5b4765f383dd7c75d8e57be4/time-in-list)**. Does what it says on the tin! Super simple time in list tracking for Trello.

**[Trello Forms](https://trello.com/power-ups/6139de588901011c01baf52f/forms-by-blue-cat)**. The easiest to use, most complete Forms solution for Trello.

listing.description:
[Epic Cards by Screenful](https://screenful.com/epics-for-trello?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup) is a **free Power-Up** that allows you to group cards into larger bodies of work, epics. As cards are completed, the progress of the work is shown in your epic card. 

**Features**

- **Create a card hierarchy** by assigning subtasks to cards
- Group cards into logical themes **across all your boards**
- Easily **find cards that are related**
- **See the progress of your work** across multiple boards

![Epic Cards by Screenful](https://app.screenful.me/integrations/trello-epics/_assets/epics_small.gif)

[See the video tutorial](https://screenful.com/epics-for-trello?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup)

 ---
   
**It's free so you can just add it to your board**. Learn more about [Epic Cards by Screenful](https://screenful.com/epics-for-trello?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup) and see also [our other free Power-Ups!](https://screenful.com/power-ups?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup)

listing.name: Google Drive
listing.description:
The Google Drive Power-Up for Trello brings your files and folders to Trello cards. Search Google Drive right from Trello and attach relevant files and folders. See real-time previews and details and click back into Google Drive. It also lets you turn your Trello board into a Google Slides presentation with one click.

- Built in file search lets you attach folders and files from Google Drive to a Trello card on any version of Trello.
- See real-time information and previews for any Google Drive files or folders attached to cards.
- Turn your Trello board into a Google Slides presentation with one click.

![screenshot](https://google-drive.trello.services/images/screenshots/Google_Drive_1.jpg)
![screenshot](https://google-drive.trello.services/images/screenshots/Google_Drive_2.jpg)
![screenshot](https://google-drive.trello.services/images/screenshots/Google_Drive_3.jpg)
![screenshot](https://google-drive.trello.services/images/screenshots/Google_Drive_4.jpg)
listing.overview: Access your Drive files for a project directly from its card, or create and attach new Drive files to a card.

listing.name: Agile Tools by Corrello
listing.description:
# Free Agile Points and WIP limits for Trello

Agile Tools by Corrello allows you to add story points and WIP Limits to Trello. It is fully integrated with Corrello [Scrum and Kanban Charts](https://trello.com/power-ups/568c2b6c7d2758a55ac48c98/agile-scrum-kanban-dashboards-charts-corrello) **[burndowns](https://app.getcorrello.com/Burndown?utm_source=trello&utm_medium=directory&utm_campaign=agile_tools_powerup_burndown)**, **[CFDs](https://getcorrello.com/cumulative-flow-diagram?utm_source=trello&utm_medium=directory&utm_campaign=agile_tools_powerup_cfd)**, **burnups**, and **[cycle time](https://app.getcorrello.com/cycle-time?utm_source=trello&utm_medium=directory&utm_campaign=agile_tools_powerup_cycletime)** charts. 

Agile Tools is **completely free** and is the perfect Power-Up for Scrum or Kanban teams using Trello (or even teams blending a mix of Scrum and Kanban :) )

Add the power-up today to take benefit of these great features:

- **Story points on Cards**. Set on the back of cards, shown on the front. Includes the ability to use a colour scale to large vs small Cards are easy to spot.
- **One click migration of story points from Scrum for Trello** or any other tool which stores points in the Card titles.
- **WIP limits** easily set in the power-up settings, or in list titles using numbers in []'s
-  **Count of Cards or Points in each List** useful for quick overview of upcoming work or past velocities.

![Features GIF](https://app.getcorrello.com/manifests/agiletools/images/agiletools.gif)

## Story Points for Trello

Easily set and see story points on all your cards. Points are shown on the front of your cards and can be easily set on the back. By default we will allow people to select any Fibonacci number for their estimates, or enter their own value. You can also set the points available for your team if you don't want to use the typical Fibonacci sequence we default to.

![Story Points on cards and lists](https://app.getcorrello.com/manifests/agiletools/images/list_points.png)

You can also opt to use a colour scale for the points on your cards. This makes it easy to see visually which cards have higher or lower estimates. We can also highlight any unestimated cards in red. This makes it really easy to spot unestimated cards for an estimation session, or to highlight unestimated cards which are being added to a sprint.


## Estimate your Scrum Sprints

Clicking on the Agile Tools button in Trello will show the number of points currently in each list. This makes it super simple to check how many points you have assigned to your current (or future) sprint, and how many are in progress right now. You can also see the number of points completed in previous sprints, we recommend creating a new 'done' list for each sprint if you want to track past velocity easily. 

Also, if you have future planned work estimated in lists on your board you can easily see from the Agile Tools button how many points are in each upcoming list.

## WIP Limits for Trello

If all you want are WIP limits you could also check out our [Kanban WIP](https://trello.com/power-ups/5e621e477907d7774380f551/kanban-wip-by-corrello) Power-Up for Trello.

Setting WIP limits is a very common approach in Kanban to encourage teams to focus on finishing work before starting something new. It can also be useful on Scrum teams for the same reason.

With Agile Tools you can set WIP limits for individual lists in Trello. We will show the number of cards and the WIP limit on the front of each card and highlight when you are at or over the WIP limit for that list

![Set WIP limits for Trello](https://app.getcorrello.com/manifests/agiletools/images/wiplimits.png)

## Integrates with Corrello for Burndowns, CFDs and more...

Agile Tools for Trello is the only power-up which integrates with [Corrello](https://trello.com/power-ups/568c2b6c7d2758a55ac48c98/agile-scrum-kanban-dashboards-charts-corrello) - Dashboards for Agile teams using Trello. Corrello can plot your Story Points on a Burndown, plus send daily emails with your latest Burndown, WIP, Slow Cards etc. Track cycle times, release burnups, your Cumulative Flow Diagram and more with a just few clicks :)

![Agile Metrics for Trello](https://app.getcorrello.com/public/images/powerup/cfd.png)

-----------

**Got questions?** drop us a line agiletoolspowerup@getcorrello.com


## What are people saying about Agile Tools?

*Software development is a messy process, planning is continuous and new Trello cards get added by the team on a daily basis. It is great to be able to **spot all unestimated cards with one click** and keep the scrum board estimated at all times. It is also extremely useful to get an **overview of the amount of points currently allocated in each Trello column**. This feature comes very handy when trying to understand whether we're putting too much work on our shoulders for our next sprint or whether it's possible to increase our scope.*
- Valentino Giudice (PM **Natural Cycles**)

----

## What are Story Points?

Story points are a way of estimating work which breaks the link between hours/days to complete and the number on the estimation. So while you may expect roughly the same number of story points completed per week for a team, you wouldn't talk about estimates in terms of hours or days.

This is important as it makes it easier for the team to discuss the estimate without getting hung up on how long the card will take to complete. Instead they can compare that task with previous completed tasks and decide which previous tasks it is most similar to in terms of the complexity/effort to deliver. Then they assign the same number of story points as those most similar previous tasks to this new task.

If you estimate in terms of hours/days it can be very easy to get drawn into discussions of **how** the work will be done and justifying the time estimate to a very high level of precision. Or to have people feel they will look stupid for thinking something will take longer than another person suggests. By discussing points relative to another completed task it becomes a bit more abstract and easier for people to have open discussions.

## How to estimate Story Points?

There are many ways to generate the estimates. The only hard and fast rule is that the estimate should be created by the team who will complete the work.

Some popular/common ways to estimate story points

### Planning poker

In planning poker each team member has cards for each of the story point options (typically 1,2,3,5,8,13,21). Each task to be estimated is shown to the team, questions are asked and answered until the team is ready to estimate it. Any additional details brought out in the discussion should be added to the task in Trello (ie limits on what is to be done, or clarifications etc.) Each team member then plays one of their cards face down. When everyone is ready you turn over the cards and see the estimates. If everyone is in agreement the estimate is added to the card. If there is disagreement you typically get the people with the highest and lowest estimates to discuss their differences until you can reach some agreement within the group. 

Having a set of reference cards is very useful here, so people can see examples of past cards which were a 1, 2, 5, etc. People can then talk about the size of each card in comparison to the reference examples.

Planning poker is a very thorough way of estimating work for a Scrum team, but can take a long time to get through a lot of cards. However, the discussions which take the time to get through would need to happen eventually. It is better to have them during a planning session than in the middle of a sprint and only then realise a card is a lot more complex than expected!

### Story Point Buckets

This is a lot more interactive and allows for less discussion up front, but can help in getting through a lot of cards in a more efficient way.

Your team will need space in front of a wall to do this and be able to stick and move cards on the wall. Start by creating buckets for each Story point value (1,2,3,5,etc) with one or more reference cards for each. Place these horizontally across the wall. The area below each story point card is it's bucket.

Then place the cards to be estimated where the team can get them and let them start picking up cards and putting them into the bucket they think is correct. Team members can also move cards they think are in the wrong bucket. After some time you should have a bunch of cards on which the team is agreed on an estimate, and some others which different people want to move. You can simply assign the relevant points to the cards which there is agreement on. Then discuss estimates on the more contentious ones.


## Why use fibonacci number for Story Points?

Great question! Fibonacci numbers are used by Scrum teams as they have the property of lower precision as the numbers increase. When comparing a task estimated as a 1 or a 2 it makes sense to worry about that extra point as it doubles the estimate. But for a task estimated as an 8 the difference between 8 and 9 is less significant. Instead we want to ask is this more like an 8, or more like a 13?

## How many story points to a day?

Although you will have a rough average for the number of story points a team can complete in a week, you shouldn't really think of it in terms of points per day or anything like that. And certainly you can't compare points from one team to another team, since the way they estimate them could lead to large differences (one teams 5 point card could be a 13 for another, even if they would complete it in the same time).

listing.description:
With [Agile Cards by Spartez](https://spartez-software.com/products/agile-cards-for-jira?utm_source=Trello&utm_medium=description&utm_content=textlink) you can now easily print and maintain physical cards on your physical board with one of the tailored templates: compact cards, board cards or full-page cards.

  Customize the look of the card by selecting which fields will be printed and change the size of elements for your specific needs. It works great for agile teams in day-to-day work, for printing vacation plans and to-do lists for everyday use.

  - Use one of the three ready-to-use templates: compact cards, board cards and full-page cards.
  - Customize which fields you want to print.
  - Resize the elements on the card.
  - Print your Trello cards to work with them on your physical boards.

Before using our Power-up you have to accept the terms of the [End User License Agreement](https://spartez-software.com/eula-latest).

listing.name: TeamGantt
listing.description:
The [TeamGantt](https://www.teamgantt.com) Power-Up gives you the ability to view and schedule your cards in a beautiful timeline.

TeamGantt is the popular project scheduling tool used by thousands of customers in over 120 countries.

+ Organize cards from multiple boards into a single, beautiful gantt chart inside Trello
+ Add project dependencies and resourcing to Trello boards
+ Sync dates and completion rates across services automatically
+ Works in all major web browsers


![Gantt Chart](https://trello.teamgantt.com/images/screenshot.gif)
![Card back](https://trello.teamgantt.com/images/card-back.png)


### Two sync modes are available:


+ **Auto Link**
Automatically sync newly created cards and tasks from one Trello board to a single TeamGantt gantt chart. Cards are synced immediately on creation. This is the easiest and most common link type. Best if you want to have all the cards in a single board displayed in a Gantt chart.

![Sync Options](https://trello.teamgantt.com/images/sync-options.png)

+ **Manual Link**
Gives you full control over when and where your cards are synced to TeamGantt. As the name implies, this sync mode requires some manual work. You will need to individually pick which cards you want to display in a timeline. This allows you to pick and choose which cards you want to see in a Gantt chart

  + Send cards from one Trello board to multiple gantt charts
  + Sync cards from multiple Trello boards to a single gantt chart 
  + Cards are not automatically synced on creation, allowing you to finalize a card's details before syncing to TeamGantt
  + Manual Link is more hands on compared to Auto Link, but it gives you the ultimate in flexibility.

### Professional Gantt Charts Loaded With Features:

TeamGantt brings the leading online Gantt chart software to Trello!

![Features](https://trello.teamgantt.com/images/TeamGantt-trello.png)
listing.overview: View your cards in a beautiful timeline with the popular project scheduling tool used by thousands of customers in over 120 countries.

listing.name: Epic Cards by Screenful
listing.description:
[Epic Cards by Screenful](https://screenful.com/epics-for-trello?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup) is a **free Power-Up** that allows you to group cards into larger bodies of work, epics. As cards are completed, the progress of the work is shown in your epic card. 

**Features**

- **Create a card hierarchy** by assigning subtasks to cards
- Group cards into logical themes **across all your boards**
- Easily **find cards that are related**
- **See the progress of your work** across multiple boards

![Epic Cards by Screenful](https://app.screenful.me/integrations/trello-epics/_assets/epics_small.gif)

[See the video tutorial](https://screenful.com/epics-for-trello?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup)

 ---
   
**It's free so you can just add it to your board**. Learn more about [Epic Cards by Screenful](https://screenful.com/epics-for-trello?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup) and see also [our other free Power-Ups!](https://screenful.com/power-ups?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=epics_powerup)
